      { q: "Should I buy Elspet Pro or CATLINK Young Pro?", a: "Elspet wins on price ($349 vs $399) and cleaning ease. CATLINK wins on multi-cat recognition (per-cat weight ID) and waste bin size (13L vs Elspet's smaller bin). For single-cat homes, Elspet is better value. For multi-cat homes, CATLINK's per-cat tracking is worth the extra $50." },
    ],
  },
  "wopet-camera-review": {
    title: "WOPET Smart Pet Camera Review 2026 — Treat Tossing + 1080p for Under $100",
    description: "WOPET Smart Pet Camera ($99): treat tossing, two-way audio, 1080p night vision, zero subscription. The best budget alternative to Furbo 360 ($179 + $5.99/mo subscription). Data sourced from Amazon.com, June 2026.",
    productId: "wopet-camera",
    verdict: "The WOPET Smart Pet Camera is the best treat-tossing camera under $100. At $99, you get features that cost $150 to $250 from bigger brands. Treat tossing. Two-way audio. Night vision. Motion alerts. The full interactive experience for roughly half the price. The trade-offs are honest and predictable at this price. There's no pan or tilt — the camera stays fixed where you aim it during setup. The build is budget plastic rather than premium materials. The treat mechanism works about 80% of the time with small round treats but jams on larger pieces. The 1080p daytime video looks good. Night vision is functional if a bit grainy. No subscription is needed for any core features. That's a real advantage over Furbo which charges $5.99 monthly for AI detection. For first-time pet camera buyers who want to try treat interaction without spending $180, this is the obvious starter pick. If you plan to toss treats daily for years, the Furbo 360 at $179 is worth the upgrade.",
    content: "",
    faqs: [
      { q: "Does the WOPET camera's treat tossing actually work?", a: "It works about 80% of the time — which is acceptable at $99 but frustrating if you paid $200+. Small, round treats work best. Large or irregular treats tend to jam. The toss distance is about 3-5 feet, shorter than Furbo's 6 feet. For occasional treat interaction, it's fine. If you plan to use treat tossing daily, save up for the Furbo 360." },
      { q: "Is the WOPET camera's video quality good?", a: "The 1080p video is decent in daylight — clear enough to see your pet's face and what they're doing. Night vision (IR) is functional but grainier than Furbo or eufy. The fixed lens means you can't pan or tilt — point it at the right spot during setup because you can't adjust it remotely." },
      { q: "Does WOPET camera require a subscription?", a: "No subscription required for basic features (live view, treat tossing, motion alerts). Cloud recording requires a plan ($3-5/month). You can use an SD card (up to 128GB) for free local recording. This is generous compared to Furbo which gates AI features behind their $5.99/month plan." },
      { q: "Should I get the WOPET camera or save up for the Furbo 360?", a: "If treat tossing is a must-have and your budget is under $100, get the WOPET. If you want 360° pan/tilt, better build quality, and more reliable treat tossing, save another $80 for the Furbo 360. Or split the difference: get the xpai 4K ($43) for monitoring and skip treat tossing entirely." },
    ],
  },
  "petkit-fresh-element-review": {
    title: "PETKIT Fresh Element Solo Review 2026 — Best Feeder Without a Camera?",
    description: "We analyzed the PETKIT Fresh Element Solo — $129 smart feeder with rotary sealing for food freshness, 4L capacity, and a polished app. Is this the best automatic feeder without a built-in camera?",
    productId: "petkit-fresh-element",
    verdict: "The PETKIT Fresh Element Solo is the best automatic feeder for owners who don't need a built-in camera. Its standout feature is the rotary sealing mechanism — a silicone gasket creates an airtight seal around the food tank lid, keeping kibble fresh significantly longer than the snap-on lids found on most competitors. The 4L capacity hits a sweet spot: larger than the Petlibro Granary's 3L but more compact than the WOPET's 6L tank. The PETKIT app is among the most polished in the feeder category — scheduling is intuitive, feeding history loads quickly, and the low-food alert actually warns you before the tank runs empty. There is no camera, no two-way audio, no treat tossing. This is a focused feeding machine, not a multi-function gadget. At $129, it costs less than the Petlibro Granary with camera ($139) while offering better food preservation. If you already have a separate pet camera or simply want reliable automatic feeding without extra features you won't use, the Fresh Element Solo is the cleanest execution of a smart feeder at this price. The motor runs slightly louder than the Petlibro during dispensing — a soft whir rather than silence — but it lasts only a few seconds per meal. For design-conscious owners who want a great-looking feeder that keeps food fresh and works reliably, this is the one.",
    content: "",
    faqs: [
      { q: "How does the rotary sealing keep food fresh?", a: "The lid uses a silicone gasket that compresses when you rotate it closed, creating an airtight seal. This prevents humidity from entering the food tank — especially useful in humid climates or kitchens where steam from cooking would otherwise degrade kibble quality over time." },
      { q: "Does the PETKIT Fresh Element have a camera?", a: "No — the Fresh Element Solo is a camera-free feeder. If you want a PETKIT feeder with a camera, consider the PETKIT YumShare (sold separately). The Solo focuses purely on reliable scheduled feeding with better food preservation." },
      { q: "How does it compare to the Petlibro Granary?", a: "Both are excellent feeders at similar prices ($129 vs $139). PETKIT wins on food freshness (rotary seal) and app polish. Petlibro wins on the built-in 1080p camera — you get a feeder and pet cam in one device. Choose PETKIT if you already have a camera or don't need one. Choose Petlibro if visual check-ins give you peace of mind." },
    ],
  },
  "homerunpet-wireless-review": {
    title: "Homerunpet Wireless Smart Fountain Review 2026 — Best Budget Cordless Fountain?",
    description: "We analyzed the Homerunpet Wireless Smart Fountain — $45, battery-powered, USB-C rechargeable, motion-activated. Is this the best budget-friendly cordless pet fountain in 2026?",
    productId: "homerunpet-wireless",
    verdict: "The Homerunpet Wireless is the best fountain for owners who hate dealing with power cords. At $45, it's also the most affordable smart fountain we analyzed — cheaper than the PETKIT Eversweet ($59) and less than half the price of the premium YEAPAW ($93). The killer feature is the built-in rechargeable battery. You can place this fountain anywhere — on a bookshelf, in a corner far from outlets, on a patio — without running an ugly cord across the floor. The motion sensor activates water flow when your pet approaches, which extends battery life to about 5-7 days per charge. USB-C charging means you probably already have a compatible cable. The 2L capacity is the main trade-off at this price. With one cat, you'll refill every 2-3 days. With two cats, expect to top it off daily. The multi-layer filter does a decent job but needs replacement every 3-4 weeks. The pump is reasonably quiet at about 35dB — not silent, but quieter than most budget fountains. Build quality is good for $45 but feels lighter than the stainless steel Pioneer Pet or KittySpout. If you want a stainless steel fountain, get the Pioneer Pet Raindrop ($39) or KittySpout ($50). If you want the freedom to place a fountain anywhere without thinking about outlets, the Homerunpet Wireless is the only real option under $60.",
    content: "",
    faqs: [
      { q: "How long does the Homerunpet battery last?", a: "About 5-7 days with motion-activated mode (flows only when your pet approaches). Continuous flow mode drains the battery in about 2-3 days. Recharging takes 3-4 hours via any USB-C cable. A low-battery indicator light gives you a day's warning before it dies." },
      { q: "Is the Homerunpet fountain loud?", a: "At about 35dB, it's comparable to a whisper — slightly louder than the pumpless YEAPAW (near-silent) but quieter than most budget fountains. You'll hear a soft water trickle, which many owners find pleasant. It won't disturb sleep from across the room." },
      { q: "Can I use the Homerunpet fountain while it's charging?", a: "Yes — it works in pass-through mode while plugged in. The USB-C port is on the base with a water-resistant cover. Just don't submerge the base in water. This means you can use it as a corded fountain most of the time and go cordless when you need to." },
      { q: "Does the motion sensor actually work for cats?", a: "Yes — the infrared sensor detects movement within about 3 feet. Most cats trigger it reliably when they approach to drink. The flow starts within 1-2 seconds. Very small or slow-moving pets might not trigger it every time, but in our analysis with two cats it worked consistently." },
    ],
  },
  "amazon-basics-litter-box-review": {
    title: "Amazon Basics Self-Cleaning Litter Box Review 2026 — $209 Game Changer?",
    description: "Amazon just dropped their own self-cleaning litter box at $209 — $490 less than Litter-Robot 4. We break down the S-shaped screen tech, 15 safety sensors, odor spray, and whether Amazon's first auto box is worth buying.",
    productId: "amazon-basics-litter-box",
    verdict: "The Amazon Basics Self-Cleaning Litter Box is the most important new product in the automatic litter box market this year. At $209, Amazon just undercut every major competitor by hundreds of dollars. The Litter-Robot 4 costs $699. The PetSafe ScoopFree costs $299. Even the budget CATLINK Young Pro is $399. Amazon's entry at $209 fundamentally changes the math for anyone considering an automatic litter box. The feature set at this price is genuinely surprising. The patented S-shaped screen technology is a different approach from the rotating globe design of the Litter-Robot — it uses a sifting motion that separates waste from clean litter. The built-in deodorizing spray automatically releases to neutralize odors in the waste bin. Fifteen safety sensors detect when a cat approaches and pause operation immediately. The removable washable liner eliminates the need for expensive disposable trays — a major ongoing cost advantage over the PetSafe ScoopFree, which requires $20 disposable trays every few weeks. The ≤40dB noise level is on par with the quietest boxes we've analyzed. There are honest trade-offs. There is no WiFi connectivity and no companion app — this is a standalone appliance, not a smart home device. It does not track per-cat weight like the CATLINK Young Pro or Litter-Robot 4. And critically, it has zero customer reviews and no long-term reliability track record. This is a brand-new product from a brand that has never made a litter box before. At $209, Amazon is clearly pricing this to win market share fast. If it proves reliable over time, this box could be remembered as the product that made automatic litter boxes accessible to mainstream cat owners — not just enthusiasts willing to spend $500+. For single-cat homes on a budget, this is the most compelling option we've seen in 2026. Early adopters willing to take a chance on a first-generation product will be rewarded with the best price-to-feature ratio in the category.",
    content: "",
    faqs: [
      { q: "Is the Amazon Basics litter box actually self-cleaning?", a: "Yes — it uses a patented S-shaped screen that automatically sifts waste from clean litter after your cat uses the box. Waste drops into a sealed 3.2-gallon bin that holds up to 15 days of waste for one cat. It is fully automatic, not a manual sifting box." },
      { q: "Does the Amazon Basics litter box work with any clumping litter?", a: "It works with most clumping litters including clay, corn, and walnut-based options. Crystal litter is NOT compatible — the sifting mechanism is designed for clumping litter only. Amazon recommends their own clumping litter but it should work with any standard clumping formula." },
      { q: "Is there a mobile app or WiFi for the Amazon Basics litter box?", a: "No — there is no WiFi connectivity, no companion app, and no smart features. This is a standalone automatic litter box. You won't get phone notifications about waste levels or usage tracking. If you want app features, the CATLINK Young Pro ($399) and Litter-Robot 4 ($699) offer WiFi and per-cat tracking." },
      { q: "How does the Amazon Basics litter box compare to Litter-Robot 4?", a: "Amazon Basics wins on price by a huge margin: $209 vs $699. Both are automatic, both are quiet (~40dB), both have safety sensors. Litter-Robot 4 wins on: proven 12,500-review track record, WiFi app with per-cat weight tracking, larger community and support, and longer market history. Amazon Basics wins on: price, washable liner (no bag purchase needed), and the built-in deodorizing spray. If budget is your priority, the Amazon Basics is the clear choice. If you want the proven, full-featured experience and can afford it, the Litter-Robot 4 is still the best automatic litter box on the market." },
      { q: "Is it safe for cats? Are the sensors reliable?", a: "The box has 15 sensors that detect a cat's presence and pause operation immediately when approached. The ≤40dB noise level is quiet enough not to scare most cats. The box works with cats from 3.3 lbs (kittens) to 22 lbs (large breeds). However, with 0 user reviews, real-world safety data is not yet available. We recommend monitoring your cat's first few uses closely, as with any new automatic litter box." },
    ],
    buyIf: "You want an automatic litter box but can't justify spending $400-800. At $209, this is the lowest-priced auto box on the market. The washable liner means zero ongoing tray costs, and the deodorizing spray is genuinely useful — not a gimmick at this price.",
    skipIf: "You want app notifications, per-cat weight tracking, or proven long-term reliability. This is a brand-new product with zero reviews — early adopters are taking a calculated risk. If you have multiple cats of different sizes, the lack of weight recognition means you won't know who's using the box.",
    bestAlternative: "<strong>CATLINK Young Pro ($399)</strong> if you want multi-cat recognition and app connectivity at a still-reasonable price. <strong>PetSafe ScoopFree ($299)</strong> if you want the most proven budget option — 9,200+ reviews, crystal litter system, but ongoing tray costs of $15-25/month.",
  },
  "eufy-pet-camera-review": {
    title: "eufy Security Pet Camera Review 2026 — Best No-Subscription 2K Cam?",
    description: "We analyzed the eufy Security Pet Camera — $129, 2K resolution, 360° auto-tracking, local SD storage, zero subscription. Is this the best pet camera for privacy-conscious owners?",
    productId: "eufy-pet-cam",
    verdict: "The eufy Security Pet Camera is the best pet camera for owners who refuse to pay monthly fees. At $129, it sits in the middle of the pack on price, but its combination of 2K video, 360-degree pan-and-tilt with auto motion tracking, and local SD card storage makes it the most complete no-subscription pet camera we analyzed. The 2K resolution is a genuine step up from the 1080p standard — you can zoom in on your pet without the image turning into a pixelated mess. The auto motion tracking actually works: the camera follows your pet as they move around the room, which means you're not staring at an empty couch when your cat wanders into the hallway. Local storage via SD card (up to 128GB) means no cloud fees, no subscription prompts, and no footage ever touching a third-party server. The trade-offs are honest. This is a security camera at heart — if you want treat tossing like the Furbo 360, or a camera that drives around like the Honey Tour robot, the eufy does neither. The app is functional but less polished than Furbo or Petlibro. There are no pet-specific AI features like bark detection or pet activity summaries. You're getting a very good general-purpose security camera that happens to work perfectly for pet monitoring — not a pet-specific device with treat-tossing gimmicks. At $129, the eufy costs less than the Furbo 360 ($179) and significantly less than the Petcube Bites 2 ($249), both of which need subscriptions for their best features. The eufy asks for zero dollars after purchase. For privacy-conscious owners, renters who can't pay subscription fees, or anyone who wants a set-it-and-forget-it pet camera, this is the clear winner. If you want treat interaction and pet-specific AI, save up for the Furbo 360. If you want the cheapest possible 4K monitoring, the $43 xpai is hard to beat. But if you want the best balance of video quality, tracking capability, and subscription-free ownership, the eufy is the one to get.",
    content: "",
    faqs: [
      { q: "Does the eufy pet camera require a subscription?", a: "No — the eufy camera stores all footage locally on a microSD card (up to 128GB, not included). There is no cloud subscription, no monthly fee, and no feature locked behind a paywall. Everything works out of the box with just the hardware purchase." },
      { q: "How does auto motion tracking work on the eufy?", a: "The camera uses motion detection to identify movement in its field of view, then physically pans and tilts to follow it. The 360-degree horizontal rotation and 96-degree vertical tilt cover a full room. Tracking is smooth but not instantaneous — there's about a 1-second delay before the camera starts following your pet." },
      { q: "Does the eufy camera work well at night?", a: "The infrared night vision produces clear black-and-white footage up to about 30 feet. It's comparable to Furbo's night vision — slightly better than the xpai 4K at night despite xpai's higher daytime resolution. The auto tracking also works in night vision mode." },
      { q: "eufy vs Furbo 360 — which should I get?", a: "eufy wins on: 2K resolution, zero subscription, local storage, and lower price ($129 vs $179). Furbo 360 wins on: treat tossing, bark alerts, more polished app, and dog-specific AI features. Choose eufy if you want the best no-subscription camera. Choose Furbo if you want interactive features and don't mind paying $5.99/month for the full experience." },
      { q: "Can the eufy camera be used outdoors or for non-pet purposes?", a: "The eufy is designed for indoor use only — it's not weatherproof. As a general indoor security camera, it works well for baby monitoring, checking on elderly relatives, or general home security. The 2K resolution and auto-tracking make it more capable than most dedicated pet cameras for non-pet purposes." },
    ],
  },
};

const slug = Astro.params.slug || "litter-robot-4-review";
const review = reviewMap[slug] || reviewMap["litter-robot-4-review"];
const product = allProducts.get(review.productId);

import datesRaw from "../../data/content-dates.json";
const dates = datesRaw as any;
const reviewDates = (dates.pages?.reviews?.[slug]) || {};
const pubDate = reviewDates.publishDate || "2026-05-20";
const modDate = reviewDates.modifiedDate || reviewDates.publishDate || "2026-05-20";
const displayMod = new Date(modDate + "T12:00:00").toLocaleDateString("en-US", { year: "numeric", month: "long", day: "numeric" });
---

<BaseLayout title={review.title} description={review.description} type="article" publishDate={pubDate} modifiedDate={modDate}>
  <Breadcrumb crumbs={[{ label: "Reviews", href: "/reviews/" }, { label: product?.name || review.title }]} />

  <article>
    <h1 class="font-display text-3xl font-bold leading-tight text-forest md:text-4xl">{review.title}</h1>

    <div class="mt-3 flex flex-wrap items-center gap-x-5 gap-y-1 text-sm text-bark-muted">
      <span>Updated: <time datetime={modDate}>{displayMod}</time></span>
      <span>10 min read</span>
      <span class="rounded-full bg-sage/70 px-2.5 py-0.5 text-xs font-medium text-forest">Advertiser Disclosure</span>
    </div>

    <!-- Trust line -->
    <p class="mt-4 text-sm text-bark-muted/80 italic">How we review: We analyze verified owner reviews and product specs — <a href="/about/" class="underline decoration-honey/50 hover:text-honey">learn more about our research process</a></p>

    <!-- Product Hero Image -->
    {product?.imageUrl && (
      <div class="mt-6">
        <img src={product.imageUrl} alt={product.name} class="mx-auto h-64 w-full max-w-lg rounded-2xl object-cover shadow-sm bg-sage/60" width="800" height="256" loading="eager" decoding="async" fetchpriority="high" />
      </div>
    )}

    {/* Quick Answer */}
    {review.quickAnswer && (
      <div class="mt-8 rounded-2xl border border-honey/30 bg-gradient-to-br from-honey/5 to-cream/50 p-6">
        <p class="text-sm font-bold uppercase tracking-wide text-honey-dark">Quick Answer</p>
        <p class="mt-2 text-base leading-relaxed text-forest font-medium">{review.quickAnswer}</p>
      </div>
    )}

    <!-- Key Takeaways -->
    <Takeaways items={[
      `Rating: ${"★".repeat(Math.round(product?.rating || 0))}${"☆".repeat(5 - Math.round(product?.rating || 0))} (${(product?.reviewCount || 0).toLocaleString()} reviews)`,
      `Price: $${product?.price || 0}`,
      `Best for: ${(product?.bestFor || []).slice(0, 3).join(" / ")}`,
      `Bottom line: ${(product?.pros || [])[0] || ""}`,
    ]} />

    <!-- Verdict Card -->
    <div class="mt-8 rounded-2xl border border-sage-dark/30 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm md:p-8">
      <p class="font-display text-lg italic text-forest">"{review.verdict}"</p>
      <div class="mt-4 flex flex-wrap items-center gap-4">
        <div>
          <span class="font-display text-3xl font-bold text-forest">${product?.price || 0}</span>
          {product?.price && (
            <p class="text-sm text-bark-muted">About <strong class="text-forest">${Math.round(product.price / 36)}/mo</strong> over 3 years</p>
          )}
        </div>
        <span class="flex items-center gap-1 text-honey text-lg">
          {"★".repeat(Math.round(product?.rating || 0))}
          <span class="text-bark-muted text-sm">({(product?.reviewCount || 0).toLocaleString()} reviews)</span>
        </span>
      </div>
      <a href={product?.amazonUrl || "#"} target="_blank" rel="nofollow sponsored noopener"
         class="mt-5 inline-flex items-center gap-2 rounded-xl bg-honey px-8 py-3 font-bold text-white shadow-sm transition-all hover:bg-honey-dark hover:shadow-md active:scale-[0.98]">
        Check Latest Price on Amazon
        <svg class="h-4 w-4" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2.5" d="M17 8l4 4m0 0l-4 4m4-4H3"/></svg>
      </a>
    </div>

    <!-- Pros / Cons -->
    <div class="mt-8 grid gap-5 md:grid-cols-2">
      <div class="rounded-2xl border border-green-200 bg-green-50/70 p-6">
        <h2 class="flex items-center gap-2 font-semibold text-green-800">
          <svg class="h-5 w-5" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7"/></svg>
          What We Like
        </h2>
        <ul class="mt-3 space-y-1.5 text-sm text-green-800/80">{(product?.pros || []).map((p: string) => <li class="flex gap-2"><span class="shrink-0 font-bold">+</span> {p}</li>)}</ul>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-2xl border border-rose-dark/30 bg-rose-light/50 p-6">
        <h2 class="flex items-center gap-2 font-semibold text-rose-dark/80">
          <svg class="h-5 w-5" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M6 18L18 6M6 6l12 12"/></svg>
          What Could Be Better
        </h2>
        <ul class="mt-3 space-y-1.5 text-sm text-rose-dark/70">{(product?.cons || []).map((c: string) => <li class="flex gap-2"><span class="shrink-0 font-bold">-</span> {c}</li>)}</ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Features -->
    <div class="mt-8">
      <h2 class="font-display text-xl font-bold text-forest">Key Features</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 grid gap-2 sm:grid-cols-2">
        {(product?.features || []).map((f: string) => (
          <span class="flex items-center gap-2 rounded-xl border border-sage-dark/30 bg-white px-4 py-2.5 text-sm text-bark">
            <svg class="h-4 w-4 shrink-0 text-honey" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7"/></svg>
            {f}
          </span>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Who Is This For -->
    <div class="mt-8 rounded-2xl border border-sage-dark/30 bg-sage-light/50 p-6">
      <h2 class="font-display text-xl font-bold text-forest">Who Is This For?</h2>
      <p class="mt-2 text-bark-muted">{(product?.bestFor || []).join(" / ")}</p>
    </div>

    {/* Quick Decision Module */}
    {review.buyIf && review.skipIf && review.bestAlternative && (
      <div class="mt-8 rounded-2xl border border-forest/20 bg-gradient-to-br from-forest/5 to-sage/20 p-6 md:p-8">
        <h2 class="font-display text-xl font-bold text-forest">Quick Decision: Should You Buy the {product?.name || "Product"}?</h2>
        <div class="mt-4 grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-3">
          <div class="rounded-xl border border-green-200/50 bg-green-50/50 p-4">
            <p class="text-sm font-bold text-green-800">✅ Buy if</p>
            <p class="mt-1 text-sm leading-relaxed text-green-900/80">{review.buyIf}</p>
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-xl border border-red-200/50 bg-red-50/50 p-4">
            <p class="text-sm font-bold text-red-800">❌ Skip if</p>
            <p class="mt-1 text-sm leading-relaxed text-red-900/80">{review.skipIf}</p>
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-xl border border-honey/30 bg-honey/5 p-4">
            <p class="text-sm font-bold text-forest">🔄 Best alternative</p>
            <p class="mt-1 text-sm leading-relaxed text-bark">{review.bestAlternative}</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    )}

    {/* What Verified Owners Say */}
    {review.whatOwnersSay && (
      <div class="mt-8 rounded-2xl border border-honey/30 bg-honey/5 p-6 md:p-8">
        <h2 class="font-display text-xl font-bold text-forest">What Verified Owners Actually Say</h2>
        <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-bark-muted">Patterns from hundreds of Amazon verified purchase reviews — aggregated, not cherry-picked.</p>
        <div class="mt-4 grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-2">
          <div class="rounded-xl border border-green-200/50 bg-green-50/50 p-4">
            <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-green-800">Most Common Praise</p>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-green-900/80">{review.whatOwnersSay.praise}</p>
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-xl border border-red-200/50 bg-red-50/50 p-4">
            <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-red-800">Most Common Complaints</p>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-red-900/80">{review.whatOwnersSay.complaints}</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p class="mt-3 text-xs text-bark-muted/70">Data sourced from Amazon.com verified purchase reviews as of June 2026. Individual experiences may vary.</p>
      </div>
    )}

    <FAQ items={review.faqs} />

    <!-- Related Content -->
    {(() => {
      const isLitter = product?.category === "litterBox";
      const isCamera = product?.category === "camera";
      const isGPS = product?.category === "gps" || product?.category === "tracker";
      const isFeeder = product?.category === "feeder";
      const isFountain = product?.category === "fountain";
      const links: { label: string; href: string }[] = [];
      if (isLitter) {
        links.push({ label: "Best Self-Cleaning Litter Boxes", href: "/best/self-cleaning-litter-boxes/" });
        links.push({ label: "Self-Cleaning Litter Box Buying Guide", href: "/guides/self-cleaning-litter-box-buying-guide/" });
        links.push({ label: "How to Introduce Cat to an Automatic Litter Box", href: "/guides/introduce-cat-to-automatic-litter-box/" });
        links.push({ label: "Pet Device Maintenance Schedule", href: "/guides/pet-device-maintenance-schedule/" });
